did.abstract: Collection contains materials mainly relating to Throssel's photographic work, including 2,481 photographs, glass plate negatives and lantern slides of the Crow and Northern Cheyenne Indians from 1902-1933.

bioghist.head: Biography of Richard Throssel
bioghist.p: Throssel (1882-1933) was born in Washington state of Cree Indian and English descent. He worked as an office clerk at the Crow Indian Reservation in south-central Montana from 1902-1910 and was adopted by the Crow tribe in 1905. While at the reservation he met photographer Edward S. Curtis, and was briefly instructed by him. Throssel became a field photographer for the Crow reservation before he established his own photography studio, the Throssel Photocraft Company, in Billings, Montana, in 1910.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Collection contains materials mainly relating to Throssel's photographic work of the Crow and Northern Cheyenne Indians from 1902-1933. Collection includes 2,481 photographs, glass plate negatives and lantern slides of daily life, ceremonies, portraits and village scenes of the Crow and Northern Cheyenne; what is now the Little Bighorn National Monument; daily life of Billings; Throssel and his family; ranching; and scenery of southern Montana and northern Wyoming (1902-ca. 1920s).

Collection also includes 12 pieces of correspondence with Throssel and of his family (1915-1916, 1928, 1954-1960); manuscripts and speeches by Throssel on Indian culture; newspaper clippings, pamphlets and other printed materials on Throssel and his photography (1900-1963, 1993); 25 paintings by Throssel of outdoor scenes and Crow Indians (1904-1933); and 1 powder horn.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: There are no access restrictions on the materials for research purposes, and the collection is open to the public.
The photographic positive images may be used by researchers. The use of glass plate negatives requires the permission of the reference archivist.

userestrict.head: Copyright Information
userestrict.p: The researcher assumes full responsibility for observing all copyright, property, and libel laws as they apply.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Materials
relatedmaterial.p: There are no known other archival collections created by Richard Throssel at the date of processing.

acqinfo.head: Acquisition Information
acqinfo.p: The Richard Throssel collection was loaned to the American Heritage Center in 1967 by his daughters, Vera Throssel and Alberta Throssel Hawkins. In 1990 Vera Throssel deeded it to the American Heritage Center.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: The collection was processed by Elizabeth Hokanson in April 1994.
The finding aid description was revised and updated and portions of the collection were digitized between 2012 and 2015 by Jamie J. Greene.

did.physdesc: 14.86 cubic ft. (6 letter boxes, 1 F24 box , 39 negative boxes, 5 shoe boxes and 4 F20 boxes).

scopecontent.p: Most of the 2,481 images in this series are contained in both pictures and negatives. Subjects of the images are mainly Native Americans and outdoor scenes from the early 1900s.
